2026-04-16 12:15:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal series path between PSU + input and switched output (wiring / PCB trace / switch contacts)'] hypothesis_explanation='The power supply module is confirmed healthy (green LED on), and the cabling polarity between modules is correct. The load module is downstream and receives the control module output, but that output never rises above ~0.36 V on the “+” line whether the switch is open or closed. This rules out a load‑side short (which would pull a good 12 V line much lower only when connected) and instead points to a failure to convey 12 V through the control module.\n\nWithin the control module, there should be a low‑resistance conduction path (through the switch and its wiring/trace) from the 12 V input terminal to the 12 V output terminal when the switch is closed. The measured ~0.36 V indicates there is no such path: the output node is effectively floating or weakly biased via leakage or the indicator LED network, and closing the switch makes no difference. The inverted‑cables indicator LED is off, consistent with correct polarity into the module, so the issue is not the indicator network but rather an open circuit in the main switched path.\n\nTherefore, the most probable root cause is an open fault (broken trace, disconnected wire, or failed/contaminated switch contacts) in the control module’s series conduction path between its 12 V input and its 12 V output. Repair/replacement of this internal connection/switch assembly in the control module should restore 12 V at the output and allow the lamp to operate.'
